en: A set of illustrations for the Quixote
Chez N. J. B. de Poilly, rue St. Jacques a l'Esperance
COMME D.Q. SE FAIT ARMER CHEVALIE PAR SON HÔTE,
3.4 DQ knighted at inn by innkeeper

Don Quixote, knelt, knighted by the innkeeper in the inn courtyard at night; also in the scene, the boy holding a candle, and both party girls (doña Tolosa with the sword and doña Molinera with the spurs).French setting; quite acceptable drawing and engraving.
1 - Captions in French and Spanish.2 - Compare with Bouttats-Clouzier's design (Paris: Compagnie des Libraires, 1700).
D. QUICHOTTE Don Quichotte ayant aperçu de loin un grand nombre de moulins...
Don Quixote, mounted on Rocinante, and Sancho, on his donkey, discover several windmills; aside, a gallant scene.French setting; Dutch windmills; quite acceptable drawing and engraving.
Nicolas Jean-Baptiste Poilly (?) (after Bouttats-Clouzier and Pierre-Charles Trémolières)
DON QUICHOTTE Le pauvre Sancho fut mis au...

Sancho blanketed by Juan Palomeque and others; don Quixote observes the scene form behind the inn wall, unable to help his squire; aside, the donkey braying.Well-known scene and composition.French setting; quite acceptable drawing and engraving.
1 - Captions in French and Spanish.2 - Compare with Bouttats-Clouzier's design (Paris: Compagnie des Libraires, 1700) and Trémolières' (Paris: Dupuis, c1733-39).
DON QUICHOTTE Don Quichotte voyant venir un cavalier...
21.2 Encounter with barber21.3 Adventure of the helmet of Mambrino

Don Quixote, mounted on Rocinante, puts Mambrino's helmet on (barber basin); Sancho observes him while the barber runs away leaving his mule abandoned; two other figures (not accurate to Cervantes' text) observe them.French setting (influenced by Coypel's designs); quite acceptable drawing and engraving.
1 - Captions in French and Spanish.2 - Compare with Coypel's design (Paris: Surugue, 1728-31).
LA FAUSSE PRINCESSE DE MICOMICON VIENT PRIER D. QUICHOTTE DE LA REMETTRE SUR SON TRONE

In Sierra Morena, Princess Micomicona (Dorotea) kneels before don Quixote begging for his help; Sancho observes them holding Mambrino's helmet (barber basin); also in the scene, the barber (disguised as Micomicona's squire with a fake beard), and the priest and Cardenio (both hidden).French setting (influenced by Coypel's design; Paris: Surugue, 1723-24); quite acceptable drawing and engraving.
1 - Captions in French and Spanish.2 - Compare with Coypel's design (Paris: Surugue, 1723-24).
Nicolas Jean-Baptiste Poilly (?) (after Bouttats-Clouzier and Charles-Antoine Coypel)
Don Quichotte / Malanbrun envoya a Don Quichotte par quatre Sauvages un Cheval...
41.1 Adventure of Clavileño41.2 DQ and SP fly on Clavileño

Don Quixote and Sancho, both blindfolded and mounted on Calvileño while Duke's servants simulate their flight with a torch and a pair of bellows; in the background, the Duke, Duchess, maidens and servants.French setting (influenced by Coypel's designs); quite acceptable drawing and engraving.
1 - Captions in French and Spanish.2 - Compare with Bouttats-Clouzier's design (Paris: Compagnie des Libraires, 1700) and Coypel's (Paris: Surugue, 1728-31).
Nicolas Jean-Baptiste Poilly (?) (after Bouttats-Clouzier and Charles-Antoine Coypel)
COMME L'INDUSTRIEUX SANCHO ENCHANTA MADAME DULCINÉÉ
10.1 SP goes in search of Dulcinea

Don Quixote knelt before three peasant girls mounted on donkeys while Sancho introduces one of them to don Quixote as the enchanted Dulcinea.French setting (influenced by Coypel's designs); quite acceptable drawing and engraving.
1 - Captions in French and Spanish.2 - Compare with Bouttats-Clouzier's design (Paris: Compagnie des Libraires, 1700) and Coypel's (Paris: Surugue, 1728-31).
Nôtre Chevalier fut tres bien reçû des Bergers...
11.1 Encounter with shepherds, real and pretended
Don Quixote and Sancho eating and drinking with several shepherds and goatherds; one of them begins to play a violin.French setting; quite acceptable drawing and engraving.
DON QUIXOTE / Vence Don Quixote el Cavallero del Bosque...
14.2 DQ defeats the knight of the Mirrors

Don Quixote orders the defeated Knight of the Mirrors (Sansón Carrasco) to go to El Toboso to prostrate himself before Dulcina; also in the scene, Tomé Cecial (disguised with a fake big nose as squire) and Sancho.French setting (influenced by Coypel's designs); quite acceptable drawing and engraving.
1 - Captions in French and Spanish.2 - Compare with Coypel's design (Paris: Surugue, 1728-31).
DON QUICHOTTE / Don Quichotte saute promptement à terre...

Don Quixote, brandishing his sword, tries to fight with a lion, but the animal remains into its cage althought the lion-keeper has opened it; in the background, sancho, don Diego de Miranda, anbd the carter running awy.French setting; quite acceptable drawing and engraving.
1 - Captions in French and Spanish.2 - Compare with Bouttats-Clouzier's design (Paris: Compagnie des Libraires, 1700).
ENTRÉE DE BERGERES AUX NOPCES DE GAMACHE

Don Quixote observes one of the dances during Camacho's wedding 8several shepherdesses with bagpipes music); aside, Sancho eating.French setting (influenced by Coypel's designs); quite acceptable drawing and engraving.
1 - Captions in French and Spanish.2 - Compare with Coypel's design (Paris: Surugue, 1723-24).
Don Quichotte / Basilio tira une courte épée...
21.1 Basilio’s deception21.2 Marriage of Basilio and Quiteria

Don Quixote orders Basilio to stay calm when he discovers that Camacho has fooled him pretending to stab himself (to get married with Quiteria); aside, Sancho protecting his food.Theatrical composition.French setting (influenced by Coypel's designs); quite acceptable drawing and engraving.
1 - Captions in French and Spanish.2 - Compare with Coypel's design (Paris: Surugue, 1723-24).
